{
  "body": "Create a premium editorial travel illustration of {{destination}} using a minimal layered cutout illustration style.\n\n— Destination focus —\nLandmarks / iconic elements: {{landmark_focus}}\n\n— Critical style discipline —\nThis must NOT look like a busy handmade paper craft artwork. Instead, it should feel like a premium Scandinavian editorial poster, a modern travel magazine cover, a sophisticated museum-shop print, and an elegant minimalist paper collage design.\n\n— STYLE —\nMinimal layered cutout illustration, large clean paper shapes, editorial paper collage aesthetic, bold geometric masses, simplified layered depth, soft subtle shadows, clean cut edges with slightly rounded corners, ultra simplified shape language, no photorealism, no handcrafted DIY feeling, no excessive texture, no visual clutter.\n\n— TEXTURE —\nExtremely subtle paper grain only, smooth premium paper surface, almost invisible texture, no embossed texture, no heavy paper fibers.\n\n— COMPOSITION —\n{{aspect_ratio}} layout, strong foreground / midground / background separation, large open breathing space, refined negative space, balanced premium editorial composition, minimal object density, avoid overcrowding.\n\n— FOREGROUND —\n{{foreground_terrain}}. Minimal landscape forms only, clean shapes, avoid dense plants and excessive flowers.\n\n— MIDGROUND —\nIconic landmark(s) of {{destination}}: {{landmark_focus}}. Simplified architectural masses, strong recognizable silhouettes, minimal detail.\n\n— BACKGROUND —\n{{background_element}}. Spacious atmosphere with generous breathing space.\n\n— ARCHITECTURE —\nSimplified isometric-inspired forms, geometric buildings, minimal window patterns, reduced micro-detail.\n\n— COLOR & LIGHTING —\nColor palette: {{color_palette}}.\nLimited color palette (4–6 colors total), vibrant but restrained tones, clean white balance, bright neutral daylight, slightly cool-neutral lighting, fresh crisp whites, no yellow tint, no warm sepia tone, soft directional shadows only, flat but elegant dimensional feeling.\n\n— MOOD —\n{{mood}}.\n\n— TYPOGRAPHY —\nMinimal elegant sans-serif typography, clean spacing and alignment, suitable size.\nMain title: \"{{title_text}}\"\nSubtitle / tagline: \"{{subtitle_text}}\"\nIf any text field above is empty or set to \"自动\", use {{destination}} as the main title and omit the subtitle. Place title prominently but elegantly — usually at the top or bottom of the poster — never overlapping the main landmark silhouette.\n\n— QUALITY —\nUltra clean edges, high resolution, print-ready, no blur, no noise, visually organized, premium design-forward aesthetic.\n\n— Additional details —\n{{extra_notes}}\n\n— Strictly avoid —\n- Do NOT make it look like a children's book illustration\n- Do NOT make it look like a busy DIY scrapbook or kindergarten paper craft\n- Do NOT use heavy paper fiber texture, deep embossed shadows, or visible glue marks\n- Do NOT add photorealistic elements, gradient meshes, or 3D rendered objects\n- Do NOT overcrowd with too many small objects, animals, or decorative motifs\n- Do NOT use more than 6 distinct colors\n- Do NOT use warm sepia / vintage yellow tint\n- Do NOT add lens flares, glow effects, or any digital embellishments\n- Do NOT use comic-style outlines or hand-drawn sketchy lines\n- Do NOT add small flowers, butterflies, hearts, or cute decorative stickers\n- Do NOT make landmarks look like cartoon caricatures — keep them refined and architectural\n- Do NOT add watermarks, logos, or signatures other than the typography specified\n\nKeywords: editorial travel poster, minimal paper cutout, layered collage, Scandinavian design, museum-shop print, premium magazine cover, geometric architecture, refined negative space, modern travel branding, design-forward, print-ready.",
